The Dynamics of Ukraine-Russian Conflict through the Lens of Demographically Diverse Twitter Data

Publisher: IEEE
PDF
Salim Sazzed

Abstract:
Due to the disastrous global impact of the recent Russia-Ukraine conflict, people all over the world are getting concerned- expressing their opinions and feelings toward it on social media such as Twitter and Facebook. To comprehend people’s perceptions and reactions, in this study, we analyze around 80000 demographically diverse tweets representing Twitter users of 7 countries across four continents. We first perform sentiment analysis to reveal how sentiments are expressed across demographically diverse tweets. We notice a similar pattern in the conveyed opinions and sentiments across the groups, constituting a high number of negative tweets citing the disastrous consequence of the war and criticism of the aggression. In addition, we investigate the presence of highly offensive words and phrases in various demographic groups. Finally, we employ two topic modeling approaches, LDA and transformer-based BERTopic, to find the most prevalent and discussed topics across users of demographic groups. We witness the presence of a diverse set of topics in the tweets of various groups, with dominant themes conveying support for Ukraine, the destructive impact of the war, and the resolution of this conflict. Our analysis reveals the feelings, thoughts, and sentiments of demographically diverse Twitter users regarding this conflict and provides insights for understanding people’s perceptions across the globe.

SECTION I.

Introduction

The recent conflict between Russia and Ukraine has drawn global attention as its causing a humanitarian crisis and deleterious effect on the global economy by triggering turmoil in financial and economic sectors across the globe (e.g., soaring wheat and gas prices [1]). The conflict escalated on February 24, 2022, with Russian forces entering Ukraine territory under the campaign of a special military operation 1 (unfortunately, no ceasefire yet as of Nov 6, 2022). Numerous entities, such as governments, organizations, and individuals, have been voicing their concerns and views on this matter. These responses are often diverse in nature, highlight myriad issues and convey sentiments and opinions of different kinds and toward various targets. Due to the integral presence of social media in our daily life and the high degree of freedom of free communication and participation space they provide [2], people often tend to express their thought and opinion through them. Thus, social media data largely reflect of people’s belief and thought.

Twitter is one of the most popular social media platforms; since its appearance in 2006, it has become a place of deliberations and a significant source of information, as millions of people have been using Twitter to share opinions. As of the second quarter of 2021, Twitter has around 206 million monetizable daily active users 2, publishing about 500 million tweets every day3. Twitter offers support to monitor and evaluate people’s views and beliefs on political phenomena [3], [4], [5], [6], [7].

Location-annotated data, such as geo-tagged social media text, provide opportunities to study the views, opinions, and feelings of users of diverse geography and socio-cultures [8], [9], [10]. In particular, geolocation information embedded in social media posts, along with the textual component, can be exploited to analyze the spatial distributions of perceptions, thoughts, and opinions on a given topic [11], [12], [13]. In this context, analyzing demographically (e.g., geographically) diverse data can provide better insights regarding the attitude and stance in territorial heterogeneity and helps in exploring spatial patterns and detecting territorial clusters [14].

As demographically diverse social media data entitle us to comprehend complex social dynamics at a broader scale, in this study, we focus on analyzing people’s perceptions and views regarding this Russia-Ukraine conflict across the globe. We collect over 120000 tweets representing users from a number of countries. Then, a number of data cleaning steps are applied to fix incomplete, irrelevant, duplicate, or otherwise erroneous data in the dataset, which ultimately yields around 80000 tweets. The dataset represents Twitter users from 7 countries: the USA, the UK, Australia (AUS), Germany (GER), France (FR), Canada (CAN), and India (IND). We analyze the data to find how demographically diverse groups express their sentiments and opinions about the conflict. We find a high presence of negative opinions, which are related to the disastrous impact of the war. Nevertheless, positive words related to supporting and helping people and peace are prevalent in the tweets of the people. We do not notice any substantial presence of offending and insulting words in the tweets of various demographic groups, only 1.5% to 4.5% tweets contain insulting words. In addition, we leverage two topic modeling approaches, LDA and BERTopic, to find the highly prevalent topics in various demographically diverse tweets. We observe the presence of various topics, such as the condemnation of aggression, support for Ukraine, misinformation, food and oil crisis, military forces, and battlefields. We notice that the tweets of various groups mostly follow similar patterns in both opinion and topic levels.

A. Contributions

The main contributions of this study can be summarized as follows-

  • We create a dataset of around 80000 short texts (i.e., tweets) representing user’s thoughts regarding the Russian-Ukraine conflict and then provide various statistics of the tweets.

  • We analyze conveyed sentiments and opinions of Twitter users across various demography regarding the conflict.

  • We study the presence of insulting/offending words in the tweets of diverse demographic groups.

  • We identify the prevailing topics across different demographic groups by incorporating BERTopic and LDA topic modeling approaches.

SECTION II.

Related Work

Analyzing social media data to understand user behaviors and responses regarding various circumstances, such as pandemics, war, conflict, or elections, is a popular research area in computational social science [15] as they largely reflect the population’s behaviors [16]. Investigation of the user’s sentiments and topics discussed can help to learn the dynamics of diverse groups representing various types of individuals. Topic modeling is a popular way of identifying the dominant topics in social media forums and discussion boards. Researchers applied topic modeling approaches in various domains, such as health informatics [17], [16] and climate change [9]. Besides, studying user’s thoughts and opinions regarding various events such as COVID [18], election [19] and climate change [9] can provide insights for decision-making and predictions.

A number of earlier studies focused on the Russian-Ukraine conflict that started in February 2014, highlighting various issues. The survey study conducted by Simmons et al. [20] in 2015 found that general people of key member nations of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) believed Russia was responsible for the ongoing conflict in Ukraine. The study revealed that although many people believed that Russia was a military threat to other neighboring states, they had reservations regarding sending arms to Ukraine.

Recent studies of the Russia-Ukraine conflict primarily focused on creating datasets from various social media platforms such as Reddit and Twitter. Park et al. [21] introduced a new corpus, VoynaSlov, by collecting over 20 million tweets and posts from Twitter and VKontakte (VK), a Russian social media platform. VoynaSlov represents content created by Russian media outlets and the general public during the 2022 Ukraine- Russia conflict. The authors described their data collection process and provided various data statistics. A Reddit dataset consisting of relevant subreddits of the ongoing Russian-Ukrainian crisis was presented by Zhu et al. [22]. The authors shortlisted 12 subreddits that contain over 300,000 posts and 8 million comments collectively into two categories, "R-U Conflict" and "Military Related". The authors noticed an apparent preference for the Pro-Ukraine stance in "R-U Conflict". A Twitter dataset related to the Russia-Ukraine conflict was provided by [23]. The dataset contains over 1.6 million tweets shared during the 1st week of the crisis. [24] presented Russia-Ukraine Crisis Weibo (RUW) dataset, with over 3.5M user posts and comments in the first release. Another Twitter streaming dataset was created by [25].

Ibar-Alonso et al. [26] analyzed people’s sentiments and emotions regarding green energy during the 2022 Ukrainian–Russo conflict that has impacted global energy policies worldwide. The authors performed a number of semantic tasks, including identifying the most frequent words and a comparative analysis regarding sentiments and emotions regarding green energy before and after the conflict. Their investigation indicated that the dispute had changed the sentiment of society regarding the transition to green energy.

Chen et al. [27] studied the evolutionary opinion dynamics in Chinese social media, Weibo, regarding the Russia-Ukraine conflict and made the dataset publicly available. The authors first clustered the Weibo texts into four categories using LDA and then retrieved opinions by extracting keywords. Afterward, they applied an opinion adversarial evolution algorithm to dynamically model the dominance degree of the opinion.

Unlike the recent studies that primarily aimed at social media dataset creation related to the ongoing Russia-Ukraine conflict, here, we focus on understanding semantic content generated by demographically diverse groups of people regarding this conflict, such as topics discussed and entities mentioned. Besides, we analyze tweets from multiple demographics to understand how opinions and sentiments are expressed across demographically diverse socio-economics and locations, which have not been explored in earlier studies.

SECTION III.

Dataset

The Twitter dataset used in this study was collected from Kaggle 4, an online platform for data scientists and machine learning enthusiasts, where various types of datasets are available. The selected dataset was supposed to contain tweets related to the Russia-Ukraine conflict between April 2022 to September 2022 (based on the provided data description). However, we found a number of irrelevant tweets in the dataset having no relation to the conflicts. Therefore, we performed another level of screening by employing two highly relevant keywords, Russia and Ukraine, as filters. Only the tweets containing either of these two words were included in the dataset.

Each tweet contains multiple attributes such as user id, location, tweet text, language, retweet and popularity counts, and hashtag information. The second preprocessing step removes non-English text from the dataset. In the third step, we utilize the location information to separate demographically diverse country-specific users. We find that the location information in the tweets does not follow any standard format, present in various forms such as city, state, country, or even as a placeholder. We exclude tweets with non-representative location information. Then using a python script, we map the state and city information (whichever is available) to country-specific representations. The final dataset contains around 80000 tweets representing users of 7 countries. The countries are chosen based on their high presence in the original dataset and demographic diversity.

TABLE I: Descriptions of the dataset representing tweets of diverse groups

Table I provides various statistics of the dataset. As we can see, the USA group contains the highest number of tweets in the dataset, around 40%. The AUS group represents the fewest tweets, about 25000 tweets only. We do not notice any difference in the length of the tweets of different groups, which can be attributed to the character limit of tweets (280 characters).

SECTION IV.

Statistical and Semantic Analysis

We perform various types of statistical and semantic analysis to comprehend the reaction of diverse groups of individuals on Twitter (Fig. 1). This analysis helps to understand people thought and concern from multiple perspectives.

Fig. 1:

Various types of content analysis

A. Most Frequent Words

Term frequency (TF) counts how frequently a term (e.g., word or phrase) occurs within a document. TF depicts the distributions of vocabulary usage and reveals the trend of topics, opinions, or attitudes. We count the frequency of the words in the tweets representing the USA, Canada, UK, India, Australia, France, and Germany groups to find the top 30 terms. Both types of terms that are (i) written as hashtags and (ii) written without hashtags are reported separately (Fig 2 and Fig 3). We tokenize the text into whitespace-separated terms and find the top occurring words. To find the words with a hashtag, we look for the presence of ’#’ associated with the word.

TABLE II: Semantic orientations of the tweets across various groups based on VADER tool

B. Sentiment Analysis

We investigate user sentiments across the tweets of different country-specific groups. The VADER (Valence Aware Dictionary and sEntiment Reasoner) sentiment analysis tool [28] is applied to determine the semantic orientation of the tweets. VADER utilizes a list of words with associated polarity scores and a number of aggregation rules to determine the polarity of a piece of text. Since VADER is particularly tuned for determining sentiments expressed in the social media text, it is highly applicable to our study.

To categorize the polarity of a tweet, we follow the guidelines provided by the authors. In VADER, a compound score below -0.05 and above 0.05 represent negative and positive sentiment, respectively. The neutral sentiment is indicated by a compound score in-between them.

Besides, we identify the most frequently occurring sentiment terminologies used by Twitter users of various country-specific groups to understand people’s attitudes toward the conflict. Two sentiment lexicons, VADER and Opinion Lexicon [29], are used to recognize sentiment words present in the tweets. The VADER sentiment lexicon consists of around 8000 opinion terms, with a polarity score ranging from -4 to +4 for each term. The Opinion Lexicon is a binary-level sentiment lexicon consisting of about 6800 words, each having a polarity score of either -1 or +1. Utilizing both lexicons separately, we report the top 10 frequently occurring positive and negative sentiment words for each of the groups.

C. Presence of Insulting Language

Besides, we examine the presence of insulting and offending words in the tweets of various demographic groups. The modified version of a list of insulting words [30] is used to identify insulting tweets ( i.e., containing at least one insulting term). Although the presence of critical tweets is expected, we aim to understand the degree and intensity of such negativity; thus, we investigate the existence of insulting and offending terms. In addition, we try to find how the usages of insulting terms vary by the demography.

D. Topic Modeling

Topic modeling is an unsupervised machine learning(ML) technique for analyzing unstructured text to identify and extract high-level semantic topics. Topic modeling is an effective way of discovering latent topics present in collections of documents. A good topic model is likely to provide human-interpretable discrete topics.

TABLE III: Top 10 most frequently occurred positive and negative sentiment words across various groups (GRP)
TABLE IV: Top insulting words and the ratios of insulting tweets across various groups

Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) [31] is one of the most popular topic modeling techniques. LDA is a generative statistical model that aims to find topics of a document based on its word-level representations. LDA relies on a Bayesian probabilistic model. It assumes that each topic has a discrete probability distribution of words, while each document is composed of a mixture of topics. LDA typically assumes the presence of a pre-defined number of topics (K) in a corpus. By the random assignment of each word to one of the K topics, LDA obtains a random representation of the topics and documents that are later iteratively optimized for a more accurate representation considering posterior probability. For the LDA, we set the number of topics in the corpus to 30.

TABLE V: Top 10 topics identified by BERTopic for each demographic group (based on the frequency of topic occurrence)
TABLE VI: Top 5 topics (each with top 10 words) in each of the demographically diverse review groups based on LDA topic modeling

BERTopic [32] is a topic modeling approach that extracts coherent topic representation through a class-based variation of TF-IDF. The BERTopic generates document embedding utilizing the pre-trained transformer-based language models, clusters these embeddings, and then creates topic representations using the class-based TF-IDF procedure. BERTopic has shown a competitive performance across a number of benchmarks. We use the PyPI 5 implementation of this package. For BERTopic, based on the author’s recommendation, the number of topics is selected automatically.

SECTION V.

Results and Discussion

Fig. 2 shows the top words for each of the country-specific groups (shown as word cloud in Fig. 2 and 3). We find that the top words present in the tweets are very similar across the groups. In addition to the mention of terms Russia and Ukraine, other terms, such as war, support, people, forces, help occur most frequently in all groups except group India. In the India group, we find a high frequency of the words like Oil, minister, foreign; nevertheless, they share common terms such as war but less frequently.

As we can see from Table II, the number of negative tweets is higher than that of positive tweets, regardless of the groups. The large presence of negative terms such as destroy and kill makes the semantic orientation of the tweets negative. Table III reveals that the types of sentiment words present in the tweets are similar for all the groups. We notice that this observation is true for both types of semantic orientations, positive and negative, and both the sentiment lexicons, Opinion Lexicon, and VADER.

We notice that the stance of Twitter users heavily leans toward Ukraine. One of the reasons can be the political views of the countries studied (in addition to other reasons, including sovereignty and humanitarian grounds). The tweets primarily exhibit support for the Ukrainian resistance, seek help to free Ukraine, wish for the victory of Ukraine, and appreciate the support of the US/NATO. Besides, the mentions of the courage and strength of the Ukrainian forces are apparent in many tweets. In addition, a number of tweets emphasize other positive aspects, such as the necessity of peace and resolution of the conflict and the importance of freedom.

Table IV shows the distributions of insulting tweets in diverse groups. We find that the percentages of insulting tweets range from 2% to 4% across various groups, which can be considered standard or expected. Although Twitter users of different demographic groups strongly criticize the action of the Russian government, they mostly refrain from using insulting or offending terms. The biggest presence of offensive tweets is observed in the AUS group, which is close to 5%, while in FRA and IND groups, it is less than 2%. Regarding the type of insulting words, we find similar kinds of words are used in various groups, such as animal, barbaric, savage, shit, stupid.

Table VI shows the top 5 topics present in each of the demographically diverse review groups based on the LDA topic modeling (out of 30 selected topic clusters). As we can see, the top 5 topics in the USA group comprising of texts seeking support and help for the Ukrainian people, invasion, woman fighters, fundraising, and western support. For the UK group, the top 5 topics are very similar to the US group; nevertheless, it also contains additional topics related to sanctions and gas prices. In the FR group, a high presence of war-related terms such as killing, soldiers, vehicles, army, and military are observed. In addition, the user mentioned supporting terms such as slava and proud. In the AUS group, in addition to the common terms, words and phrases referring to the consequence and effect of war, such as children, destroyed, cost, and needs are expressed.

BERTopic shows similar patterns in the discussed topics across various groups (Table V). Some of the common topics across the groups include support for Ukrainian resistance, misinformation, woman pilot, donation, food shortage, etc. The harsh criticism toward the Russian president is one of the prevailing topics (e.g., PutinWarCrime, PutinWarCriminal, PutinButcher) in most groups.

SECTION VI.

Summary, Conclusion and Future Work

The Russian invasion of Ukraine has rendered much discussion across the world from various standpoints- people are following this ongoing conflict closely. In addition to being apprehensive about the humanitarian crisis, people are also observing their government’s stance and handling of economic and financial issues induced by this conflict. To understand people’s thoughts and concerns, in this study, we aim to shed light on the views of Twitter users of diverse demographics through investigation from multiple perspectives. We analyze around 80000 Russia-Ukraine conflict-related tweets, representing people from 7 countries: the USA, UK, Canada, France, Italy, Germany, and India. The sentiment analysis shows that both positive and negative sentiments are prevalent in the tweets, with a dominance of negative feelings toward this conflict and aggression. For example, Twitter users across the demography are expressing their concerns about the disastrous impact of the conflict. The positive sentiments depict humanitarian support for the Ukrainian people, freedom, resistance of the Ukrainian people, and desire for peace. The topic modeling reveals a myriad spectrum of topics in various diverse groups, such as mentions of battlegrounds, invasion, air battles, fundraising, western allies, sanctions, gas and oil prices, killing and destruction, freedom and democracy, media, and disinformation. Our analysis and findings reveal the opinion of people around various demographic and their concerns regarding the conflict. Note that, as we considered only the English tweets, the dataset may be biased towards the English-speaking international view. Besides, other than India, the other countries do not have a historically favorable relationship with Russia; thus, this study primarily reflects the views of the people who are not very friendly towards Russia. In our future work, we will analyze tweets from more demographics (including countries with a more favorable view toward Russia) and perform temporal analysis to see how people’s perceptions change over time.
